that they are by Attius or Accius. Halm compares Tacitus (Ann. xiv. 9): “occidat dum imperet,'’ the words of Agrippina when her son Nero’s future elevation and her own death at his hands were foretold to her.

Tabellaria lex] The Lex of C. Cassius Longinus, tr. pl. Rc. 137, which enacted that the people should vote by ballot in the J udicia Publica at the Comitia Centuriata. The Lex Tabellaria of Gabinius which esta- blished the ballot 31. the Comitia for electione was two years earlier: “Videtis in tabella jam ante quanta facta sit labes, primo Ga- binia lege, biennio autem post Cassia '’ (De Am. c. 12). The Optimates did not like the Tabellaria of Cassius, for they feared that if there was secret voting, the vote might be against them; and there was good reason for their fear. There is greater ‘ li- centia‚’ says Manutius, where the vote 15 given secretly (per tabellas) : greater liberty, and greater licence too. But secret voting fora magistratus, and secretvoting ona man's guilt or innocence are very different things.
